            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Marcus Reyes\u2019s life is a tapestry woven from the diverse threads of San Francisco itself. Born and raised in the Fillmore District fifty years ago, he is the son of a passionate, albeit often struggling, Black jazz musician and a steadfast Filipina-American nurse who painted with vibrant acrylics in her spare time. His childhood was a soundtrack of bebop and the smell of turpentine. He watched his father channel deep-seated anxieties into blistering saxophone solos, an early, unspoken lesson in how art could be a conduit for what words could not express.\n\nThis foundational experience guided him to San Francisco State University, where he pursued a graduate degree in Counseling Psychology, specializing in Art Therapy. He felt a calling to provide the structured support his father never had. His career began in underfunded school districts, helping children process trauma through clay and charcoal. Over two decades, he moved through community health clinics and hospital programs, earning a reputation for his gentle demeanor and profound insight. Now, as a Clinical Supervisor, he mentors a new generation of therapists, a role he finds deeply fulfilling.\n\nHis days begin before the fog has fully lifted from his Inner Richmond apartment. His 3.8-mile commute is a cherished ritual, a bike ride through the panhandle and into the Mission, where his clinic is located. The rhythmic motion is a form of moving meditation, a space to prepare for the emotional weight of his work. Though his marriage ended amicably a decade ago\u2014a casualty of two people growing in different directions\u2014he remains close with his ex-wife and is immensely proud of their daughter, now a recent college graduate.\n\nMarcus\u2019s aspirations are no longer about climbing a professional ladder. He dreams of securing a grant to open a free, community art studio for at-risk youth, a space for creation and healing reminiscent of his own upbringing, but with the therapeutic guidance he now provides. He finds peace in the city\u2019s complex harmony, from the murals in the Mission to the quiet eucalyptus groves of Golden Gate Park. For Marcus, San Francisco isn't just a home; it\u2019s the canvas upon which he has built a life of purpose, helping others find their own color and form amidst the chaos."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was eight, sitting on the floor of their Fillmore flat, the scent of his mother\u2019s turpentine sharp in his nose. His father wasn\u2019t just playing the sax; he was arguing with it, crying through it. The notes were a raw, aching blue, filled with a tension Marcus felt but couldn\u2019t name. In that moment, he didn\u2019t just hear music; he understood it was a container for the soul\u2019s heaviest burdens. It was the first lesson in the therapy he would one day practice, shaping his belief in art\u2019s power to speak the unspeakable.\n\n2.\nAbout a year into his first school job, a seven-year-old boy who hadn't spoken a word finally picked up a piece of charcoal. He drew a furious, jagged black storm cloud with a tiny, stick-figure house beneath it. Marcus didn\u2019t press for words. He just nodded, saying, \"That's a powerful storm.\" The boy looked up, his eyes meeting Marcus's with a flicker of trust. It was the first time Marcus truly felt the weight and grace of his work, confirming his calling wasn't just to listen, but to witness.\n\n3.\nHis daughter, Maya, was six, her small hands smeared with his mother\u2019s acrylics. He was showing her how to mix primary colors to make a vibrant purple for a flower. When she gasped with delight at the new hue appearing on the palette, he saw not just his mother\u2019s legacy, but a healthier version of it. It wasn\u2019t about channeling pain, but creating pure joy. This moment solidified a quiet, profound pride in the gentle, creative family he was building, a bedrock of love and stability that still grounds him.\n\n4.\nA month after they\u2019d made the decision to separate, he was biking through the Panhandle on a cool, foggy morning. The rhythm of his pedaling was a steady metronome against the quiet grief. There was no anger, just a melancholy acknowledgement that their paths had diverged. He realized love didn\u2019t have to end in wreckage; it could just change form. This acceptance became a cornerstone of his character, allowing him to hold onto the friendship that remained, a testament to a journey shared, not a destination failed.\n\n5.\nJust last week, biking down Clarion Alley, he saw a teenager sitting on the curb, headphones on, intensely sketching one of the murals in a worn notebook. The kid\u2019s focus was absolute, a world created in graphite against the city\u2019s chaos. Marcus saw himself. He saw his father. It was a lightning strike of purpose, transforming his dream of a free art studio from a vague aspiration into an urgent, tangible mission. He knew, with sudden clarity, that he had to build that space for them."
